==English==

===Etymology===
From [[Middle English]] ''practizen'' (variant of ''practisen'') &larr; [[Middle French]] ''pra''(''c'')tiser'' &larr; [[Latin]] ''prāctizāre'', an alternative of ''prācticāre'', derived from ''prāctica'' 'practical work' (&larr; [[Greek]] ''πρακτικη'' (''prāktikē''), a nounal variant of adjective ''πρακτικός'' (''praktikós'') 'practical').

===Alternative spellings===
* [[practice]] ([[American English]])

===Usage note===
In [[Commonwealth English]], '''practise''' is never used as a noun.  The form used is '''[[practice]]''', the same as in American English.

===Verb===
{{en-infl-reg-other-e|practis|e}}
:{{UK}}: This spelling is only used in [[Commonwealth English]].

# To repeat an activity as a way of improving one's skill.
#:''You should '''practise''' playing piano every day.''
# To perform or [[observe]] in a [[habitual]] fashion.
#:''They gather to '''practise''' religion every Saturday.''
# To pursue a [[career]].  (Most commonly refers to [[law]], Fine Art or [[medicine]]).
#:''She '''practised''' law for forty years before retiring.''
# {{archaic}}: To [[conspire]].

